During my vacations I always see flood of holidaymakers. So I was just wondering, how many tourists are visiting this land. One day I occasionally ran into some interesting statistics about the tourists in this land, this information are provided by its official statistical agency . Specifically, there are annual statistical data about foreign tourists who came from 10 different countries and have visited Baden-Württemberg since 1960. Actually the data can be treated as several time series. So let 's take a look, what the data can tell us. In this post I 'm focusing on the number of tourists as well as the number of overnight. I will first visualization of the trends of the given time series, then conduct some basic time series analysis. At the end of this post I will try to forecast the average number of overnight for French tourist in next 4 years. 1) Data reading and preoprocessing Because the data originally was published in a complex html table, I just copied and pasted the data to several csv files and did some simple preprocessing. It is a very interesting phenomenon. However this seems to be unaccountability. If you look at Japan and Italy, they also have a high correlation 0.713669. But these two countries are almost ten thousands of kilometers apart, and even have two totally different languages and cultures. Reader of this post may ask a question: How do they have such kind of tacit agreement? Note that correlation is not causation, meaning that just because two things appear to be related to each other doesn't mean that one causes the other. Furthermore, the correlation what we have could be a so-called spurious correlation , which is common problem especially for time series analysis. In exploring relationships between two time series, we should never directly observe this correlation in the first place, indstead we have to remove trend of the data at first.
